div.div:
The above graph uses complementary sets to generate a simple variant combination graph (either one original component set is used or the other alternate set, either one combination method is used or the alternate, where there are only two options).
Other variables of these graphs of multiplication methods beyond component sets and combination method/algorithm include:
- alternate graph format (like an intersection count graph or a butterfly graph)
- specific input cases (like patterns/shortcuts of multiplying 10s to partially determine digits without multiplication of all digits)
- relevant data types (does this multiplication method hold for all number types)
- ratio of digits required to be multiplied
- specific digits required to be multiplied
- combination order
- combination method/algorithm type (partial multiplication/addition, only addition, only multiplication, etc)
- partial or complete subsets (are partial multiplications (like multiplying hundreds before tens digit) used, involving breaking the problem into multiple sub-multiplications and an addition)
- problem-solving intent or workflow implemented by the combination method/algorithm
These variables can be identified automatically for a problem and the graph of these variable combination variants can be generated automatically, using definitions/similarities/requirements/problem-solving intents (using generative queries like 'what is a multiplication method for each problem-solving intent or each variable combination variant' or 'what is a multiplication method for new variants of this spectrum variable, given this partial set of variants and these requirements/definitions/limits').
Overall, the graph format is the interesting variable to identify patterns in, like which requirements/similarities/definitions are used to generate the graph.
Otherwise evaluating which formats relate to which quantities logically is useful, like whether a spectrum makes sense for a variable or whether there is no order like increasing order that might make a spectrum relevant.
